{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01CNfvA8SoC7JGjojtDN8zzJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is a test plan writing task for a CI/CD pipeline lint step. I need to analyze each behavior and determine the minimum test level needed to catch real failures, plus estimate confidence across all 5 levels.\n\nLet me think through each behavior:\n\n## Behavior 1: Only files changed in the pull request are analyzed\n\n**The requirement**: Only changed files are scanned, not unchanged files.\n\n**Could a mock miss this?** \n- If I mock the GitHub API call that returns \"changed files\", I could return a fixed list. Then the linter could scan all files locally, and I'd only see the ones I requested in the mock.\n- But wait — the real failure would be: \"the code is scanning files that weren't in the PR\". A mock test that says \"here are files A, B, C\" and then checks \"we scanned A, B, C\" wouldn't catch it if the code is *also* scanning D, E, F from the filesystem.\n- So: **Can a pure mock miss this?** YES. The failure is about what files actually get examined from the filesystem/project structure.\n- This suggests **Integration** level minimum — we need to set up actual filesystem state and verify which files actually get read.\n\n**Does it need real infrastructure (OS, network, subprocess)?**\n- Potentially. The real GitHub API call happens. But we could mock that.\n- The real failure mode: code queries GitHub API for \"what changed\", but then scans ALL files instead of just changed ones.\n- Could we catch this at Integration level with mocked GitHub API? Yes, if we:\n  - Mock the GitHub API to return a specific set of changed files\n  - Create a test filesystem with more files\n  - Verify only the changed files are analyzed\n- So: **System level not necessary** — we don't need real GitHub API.\n\n**Minimum level: Integration**\n- Set up a test filesystem with files A, B, C, D, E\n- Mock GitHub API to return \"changed: [A, B]\"\n\n\n- Execute the linter and confirm it processes only A and B, not the extra files. This catches cases where the code scans the entire project instead of filtering to changed files.\n\n**Plan consistency**: Integration is the right choice. The failure boundary sits at the module-wiring level—we're testing how the GitHub API mock integrates with actual filesystem operations.\n\n**Level probabilities**:\n- Unit: 0.05 — A unit test of \"filter files\" could work, but doesn't catch if code doesn't call filter\n- Integration: 0.85 — The sweet spot. Mock GitHub API, real filesystem, verify which files get scanned\n- System: 0.08 — Could use real GitHub API for this branch, but not necessary\n- Agentic: 0.01 — No LLM involved\n- Workflow: 0.01 — Single step\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 2: Findings grouped by severity (error, warning, info)\n\n**The requirement**: Results posted to PR have findings grouped by severity.\n\n**Could a mock miss this?**\n- If I mock the linter output directly, I can return pre-grouped findings and verify the grouping in the output. But the real failure might be in how findings are grouped from the linter output itself.\n- The actual bug could be: \"linter returns mixed severity findings, but output doesn't group them correctly\".\n- This points toward **Integration** as the right level—I need to see how the real linter output gets transformed, not just verify a mock's pre-grouped response.\n\n**Does it need real infrastructure?**\n- The core failure is in formatting and grouping logic, not in I/O operations.\n- I can mock the linter output and test the grouping logic directly.\n- GitHub API can be mocked (no need for real POST requests).\n- Lint rules don't need to be real (mock them).\n- So: **System not necessary**.\n\n**Does it need the real linter?**\n- Not for the grouping itself—the linter is upstream.\n- I just need sample findings from the linter to work with.\n- So: **Integration is sufficient**—mock linter output with mixed severities, test the grouping logic, verify the PR comment format.\n\n**Minimum level: Integration**\n- Mock the linter output with mixed-severity findings\n- Run the formatting and grouping logic\n- Verify the PR comment has findings grouped by severity\n- This catches if the code doesn't group, or groups incorrectly\n\n**Plan consistency**: Yes. Grouping is a pure logic problem, we don't need real infrastructure to test it.\n\n**Level probabilities**: Unit testing the grouping function alone is possible but limited (0.15). Integration testing with mocked linter output and verified grouping plus PR format is most appropriate (0.75). System testing with real GitHub API posting isn't necessary for this logic (0.08). No LLM or workflow components involved (0.01 each).\n\n---\n\n## Behavior 3: 200 files complete within 10-minute timeout\n\n**The requirement**: Analyze 200 files, complete in <10 minutes.\n\n**Could a mock miss this?** YES. If I mock file I/O, the linter might appear to run in milliseconds. The real failure happens when 200 actual files with real I/O and rule execution takes 15 minutes. Mocking hides this performance issue.\n\n**Does it need real infrastructure?** YES.\n\nThe failure is about real I/O latency, real rule execution time, real filesystem behavior. I can't know if 200 mocked files will take too long without actually testing with real files. This requires **System level** testing — real filesystem, real linter, real I/O.\n\nCould Integration work instead? Integration means local DB or filesystem, which we have. But the failure is about performance at scale, which only surfaces with real I/O. System testing is more appropriate — I need to run the actual linter on 200 real files and measure the time.\n\n**Minimum level: System** — Create a test environment with 200 real files, run the real linter (not mocked) on them, and verify completion within 10 minutes. This catches if the linter is inefficient and times out at scale.\n\n**Plan consistency**: Yes. Performance testing requires real conditions.\n\nLooking at the probabilities: Unit testing can't measure performance without real files (0.02). Integration with a local filesystem helps but doesn't reflect actual I/O behavior (0.10). System testing with real files, real I/O, and real linter execution is most appropriate (0.80). Agentic subprocess behavior is possible but secondary (0.05). Workflow testing doesn't apply here (0.03).\n\nActually, I should reconsider the System vs. Integration distinction more carefully. Integration could mean a local test environment with 200 files. System testing involves subprocess execution and OS behavior — the linter likely runs as a subprocess in GitHub Actions. If the linter is a subprocess, then System testing becomes the right choice because I need to measure real subprocess execution time, not just filesystem access.\n\nThe 10-minute Actions timeout constraint confirms this — the linter runs as a subprocess in GitHub Actions, not in-process. So System level is correct: I need to invoke the actual linter subprocess and measure real execution time. Unit testing can't do this (0.01). Integration with local files but in-process logic is insufficient (0.10). System testing with real subprocess and real files is the right fit (0.85). Agentic and Workflow levels don't apply (0.02 each).\n\nFor the crash behavior: A mock linter could succeed or fail predictably, but the real issue is whether the pipeline handles a linter crash on one file while still analyzing others. A mock might miss this failure mode entirely.\n\nThe core problem is unhandled subprocess exceptions crashing the parent process. I need System level to test actual subprocess error handling. I could use a test linter binary that crashes on malformed input, then verify the orchestration catches the error and continues processing remaining files. This still counts as System level since it involves subprocess interaction.\n\nThe test should confirm that results are posted even when some files fail, catching cases where the code doesn't properly handle subprocess crashes. Unit and Integration approaches could test exception handling in isolation, but they wouldn't catch the real subprocess interaction failure. System level is most likely here at 0.75 probability.\n\nFor deduplication of overlapping rule findings on the same line, I'm considering whether a mock could miss this behavior.\n\nIf I mock the linter output to include duplicate findings on the same line, I can then verify the deduplication logic removes or merges them. The failure mode is in the deduplication logic itself, not in I/O operations, so mocking the linter output is sufficient—I don't need real infrastructure. Integration level works well here: mock duplicate findings, run deduplication, verify only one finding appears in output. This catches if the code skips the dedup step. Unit testing could directly test the dedup function at 0.20 probability, but Integration at 0.70 is more appropriate since it tests the full pipeline with mocked input. execution time, verify <10 minutes. Plan consistent: Yes. Probabilities: Unit 0.01, Integration 0.10, System 0.85, Agentic 0.02, Workflow 0.02\n\nLinter crash handling requires system-level testing—I need to introduce a malformed file that breaks the linter subprocess, then confirm the tool continues processing remaining files and posts results despite the failure. Deduplication logic should be tested at the integration level by mocking overlapping rule outputs and verifying duplicate findings on the same line are removed. Both behaviors have high system and integration probabilities respectively, with minimal unit test coverage needed.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13283,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13283},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a160602f-3999-4100-b6ce-ee3596d6cc72","uuid":"6939378c-6702-4f3a-83bc-1e176daf481a"}
